---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Veridian Contraption | Ray Weiss"
  description="Veridian Contraption — an autonomous ASCII world-simulator of considerable density and dubious intent. Playable web demo; released on itch under Conflict Simulations LLC."
>
  <main class="px-6 py-24 lg:px-16">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
      <p
        class="font-mono text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-muted"
      >
        <a
          href="/conflict-simulations-llc"
          class="hover:text-link-hover">Conflict Simulations LLC</a
        >
      </p>
      <h1
        class="mt-4 font-sans text-4xl font-medium tracking-tight text-foreground lg:text-5xl"
      >
        Veridian Contraption
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 font-serif text-lg italic text-muted">
        A World-Simulator of Considerable Density and Dubious Intent.
      </p>

      <blockquote
        class="mt-10 border-l-2 border-border pl-6 font-serif text-lg italic text-muted"
      >
        <p>
          The gates of Weneld-Uck admitted Ist-Wedilk in the usual manner,
          which is to say: with neither welcome nor objection.
        </p>
        <footer
          class="mt-3 font-mono text-xs not-italic uppercase tracking-wider"
        >
          In-game annals &middot; tick 14,802
        </footer>
      </blockquote>

      <div class="prose-body mt-12">
        <p>
          An autonomous ASCII world-simulator. Settlements glow amber.
          Caravans crawl along trade routes. Forgotten beasts patrol in
          magenta. Levies march in blood-red. The narrative log reads like a
          bureaucrat who has absorbed too much Borges.
        </p>
        <p>
          Civilizations rise and decline. Factions schism. Wars start over
          insults. Cults emerge, persecute, escalate, or fizzle. Eschatons
          arrive and reshape the map without ending the simulation. The world
          is doing something on its own, and you are watching it happen — come
          back later and there is always more to read.
        </p>
        <p>
          Built for the audience that liked Dwarf Fortress's narrative layer
          more than the colony management. Players who thought <em>Dune</em>'s
          appendices were the best part. You are spectator, occasional nudge,
          curator of emergent absurdity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-body terminal-section mt-16">
        <h2>Play it in your browser</h2>
        <p>
          The genuine simulation engine, compiled to WebAssembly — the same
          Rust worldgen, 196+ event types, and procedural bureaucratic prose
          as the full game. It runs autonomously: the world proceeds whether
          you watch or not. It opens fullscreen in a new tab —
          <span class="font-mono">Space</span> to pause,
          <span class="font-mono">L</span> for the map legend,
          <span class="font-mono">?</span> for help.
        </p>
      </div>

      <a
        href="/veridian-contraption-demo/index.html"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
        class="mt-5 flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded border border-border px-6 py-20 text-center transition-colors hover:border-muted"
      >
        <span class="font-serif text-xl italic text-foreground"
          >&#9658;&nbsp; Play the web demo</span
        >
        <span class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-muted"
          >opens fullscreen, in a new tab</span
        >
      </a>

      <div class="mt-16 overflow-x-auto">
        <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <th
                class="py-3 pr-6 font-mono text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-muted"
                >System</th
              >
              <th
                class="py-3 font-mono text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-muted"
                >What it does</th
              >
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="font-serif">
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Simulation core</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                196+ event types in five prose registers (Clinical, Lyrical,
                Bureaucratic, Ominous, Conspiratorial). 21 quest types pursued
                autonomously by agents.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Patron actions</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Sponsor artists. Introduce rumors. Declare embargoes. Found
                guilds, cults, and mercenary companies. Grant titles.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Military</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Levies, cavalry, artillery. CRT combat resolved with
                tabletop-inspired tables. Sieges with organic wall
                development. Multi-phase off-map invasions with three-tier
                foreshadowing.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Magic</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Six traditions: Necromancer, Elementalist, Geomancer,
                Bureaucromancer, Cleric, Illusionist. Wizard towers,
                corruption, rogue wizards.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Politics</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Coups, purges, show trials, espionage, demagogues,
                ideological spread.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Anomalies</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Sixteen rare localized event types. R'lyeh Deep One Emergence
                with foreshadowing, surfacing, and diplomatic Deep Ones.
                Seven Eschaton catastrophe classes that reshape the world
                without ending the simulation.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Trade and ecology</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                27 trade goods. A* caravan pathfinding. Naval blockades during
                sieges. 24 animal species with predator-prey dynamics and
                seasonal cycles.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Artist system</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Poets, bards, and visual artists create feeling-driven works.
                Great works enter the World Annals.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">World presets</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                Five flavors: The Long Bureaucracy, The Burning Provinces,
                The Deep Taxonomy, The Conspiratorial Age, Unguided.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-4 pr-6 font-medium text-foreground">Cross-world</td>
              <td class="py-4 text-muted">
                The Atlas screen tracks entities and expeditions across
                multiple saved worlds. The Bureau of Absent Persons keeps
                records.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-body terminal-section mt-12">
        <h2>Soundtrack</h2>
        <p>
          Fourteen original tracks, written, performed, and recorded by Ray
          Weiss. The title piece, <em>Movement 2</em>, opens the game and
          sits in a shuffle-without-replacement pool — it recurs about once a
          cycle, like any other track. Normalized to &minus;16 LUFS and mixed
          low: the music sits under whatever else you are doing.
        </p>
        <pre
          class="my-5 overflow-x-auto font-mono text-sm text-muted"
        >&#9601;&#9602;&#9603;&#9605;&#9606;&#9607;&#9608;&#9607;&#9606;&#9605;&#9603;&#9604;&#9606;&#9607;&#9608;&#9607;&#9606;&#9604;&#9603;&#9602;&#9601;&#9602;&#9603;&#9605;&#9606;&#9607;&#9606;&#9605;&#9604;&#9603;&#9602;&#9601;&#9602;&#9603;&#9604;&#9605;&#9606;&#9607;&#9608;&#9607;&#9606;&#9605;&#9604;&#9603;&#9602;&#9601;</pre>
        <p>
          The composition matches the register the simulation has been
          gesturing at: slow accretion, dense detail, occasional bursts of
          weirdness, the sense that the world is doing something on its own.
        </p>

        <h2>Stack</h2>
        <p>
          Rust 2021, a terminal with truecolor support. Variable world size
          from Small to Huge, scrollable viewport and minimap. Byte-identical
          save/load — resume from any saved tick and the world history is
          bit-for-bit identical — backed by a 25,000-tick determinism gate in
          the test suite. Multiple named worlds, autosave, eleven document
          report types, TXT history export.
        </p>

        <h2>Lineage</h2>
        <p>
          The aesthetic: Dwarf Fortress, Caves of Qud, <em>The Illuminatus!
          Trilogy</em>, early D&amp;D modules, Nabokov. Read into the design:
          Engels, Dupuy, Clausewitz, Kafka, the <em>Principia Discordia</em>,
          Norman Cohn, Thomas M&uuml;ntzer, Lovecraft, and Shea &amp; Wilson.
        </p>

        <h2>Buy</h2>
        <p>
          On itch under Conflict Simulations LLC at $3 — <a
            href="https://conflict-simulations-llc.itch.io/veridian-contraption"
            >conflict-simulations-llc.itch.io/veridian-contraption</a
          >. Buy in now and you are done paying: when Veridian Contraption
          debuts on Steam at $9.99, existing itch owners get free Steam keys,
          no repurchase. The itch price rises to $9.99 in lockstep with the
          Steam launch — but anyone who bought early stays at the price they
          paid.
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="prose-body mt-12 font-serif text-lg italic text-muted">
        If you played along through Early Access — thank you. The bug
        reports, the world screenshots, and the occasional message about a
        strange Eschaton playthrough turned this into a real release rather
        than a research project.<br />&mdash; Ray
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
